Details
1. Rules and exact conditional order
- Must check the "both" condition before single divisibility checks to avoid returning only "Fizz" or "Buzz" when both apply.
- Explicit check options (equivalent):
  - If (i modulo 15 == 0) output "FizzBuzz";
  - else if (i modulo 3 == 0) output "Fizz";
  - else if (i modulo 5 == 0) output "Buzz";
  - else output i.
- Order matters: if using separate tests without short-circuiting, ensure concatenation approach evaluates both divisibility conditions reliably.

2. Iteration and complexity
- Single loop from 1 to n. Time complexity O(n). Space complexity O(1) if streaming output, O(n) if collecting results into an array.
- Per-iteration operations: up to two modulo operations and constant-time branching.

3. Input validation
- Enforce type: require numeric input. If language supports, require integer type or check via integer-test function.
- Recommended validation policy:
  - If value is not a number: throw TypeError.
  - If value is a number but not an integer: throw TypeError or coerce by flooring explicitly (choose and document behavior).
  - If value < 1: return empty array or throw RangeError depending on API contract; prefer returning empty array for non-positive ranges in simple libraries.

4. Edge cases and variations
- Starting index: canonical implementations start at 1; allow configurable start index if needed.
- Zero: 0 is divisible by any non-zero integer; decide treatment (0 -> "FizzBuzz" if included) and document.
- Large n: watch for integer overflow or performance when collecting large arrays; stream output instead for very large ranges.
- Extensions: add rules for other divisors (e.g., 7 -> "Bazz") or digit-containing rules (numbers containing 3 triggers fizz) by adding additional checks.

5. Implementation signature and behavior
- Suggested API signature (language-agnostic): fizzBuzz(n: integer) -> array of strings
  - Parameters: n (integer, >=1)
  - Returns: ordered array of length n where index i-1 corresponds to input i and each element is either the string "Fizz", "Buzz", "FizzBuzz" or the decimal representation of i.
  - Errors: throw TypeError if n is not a number or not an integer; optionally throw RangeError if n < 0.

Supplementary details
- Example streaming pattern: for i in range(1,n): compute output string and write to stdout or yield it from a generator to avoid large memory usage.
- Concurrency: not applicable; operations are CPU-bound and cheap per item.
- Testing: verify sequences for n values including 1, 3, 5, 15, 16 and large boundary values. Include property-based tests: for all i, if output is "Fizz" then i % 3 == 0 and i % 5 != 0, etc.

Reference details (implementation patterns and exact checks)
- Exact divisibility checks: i % 15 == 0 or (i % 3 == 0 && i % 5 == 0). Either is allowed; use i % 15 == 0 when both checks are common and efficient.
- Function signature example (formal): fizzBuzz(n: integer) -> string[]
  - Parameter validation: if typeof n !== 'number' or !Number.isInteger(n) -> throw TypeError('n must be integer'); if n < 1 -> return [] or throw RangeError('n must be >= 1') depending on API.
- Output mapping rules precisely: mapping(i) =
  - "FizzBuzz" when i % 15 == 0
